--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Ilja Preuss&quot; &lt;preuss@d...&gt; wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; A public method is the core responsibility of a class. If we extract a
&gt; private method, that private method basically provides a service to the
&gt; public method.
&gt; 
&gt; It&#39;s true that we can remove duplication in a class by extracting
private
&gt; methods. Often, though, if we introduce the right abstraction, we
find that
&gt; the service provided can suddenly be used by other classes, too.
&gt; 
&gt; Does that sound reasonable?
&gt; 

Sounds more like speculative design and/or rearranging the chairs
without any clear immediate benefit. 

Ron Jeffries C# implementation (or one of them) of the Bowling Game
problem contains several private methods:

    private int PinCount(int pinPosition) {
        return (int) rolls[pinPosition];
    }

    private bool Strike(int rollIndex) {
        return PinCount(rollIndex) == 10;
    }

    private bool Spare(int rollIndex) {
        return PinCount(rollIndex) + PinCount(rollIndex+1) == 10;
    }

    private int FrameSize(int rollIndex) {
        if (Strike(rollIndex)) return 1;
        return 2;
    }

Ignoring the constructor of the class, there appear to be two public
methods and four private methods. Here&#39;s his Score method:

    public int Score() {
        int rollIndex = 0;
        int total = 0;
        for (int frame = 0; frame &lt; 10; frame++, rollIndex +=
FrameSize(rollIndex)){
            if ( Strike(rollIndex) ) {
                total += 10 + PinCount(rollIndex+1) +
PinCount(rollIndex+2);
            } else if ( Spare(rollIndex) ) {
                total += 10 + PinCount(rollIndex+2);
            } else {
                total += PinCount(rollIndex) + PinCount(rollIndex+1);
            }
      }
      return total;
    }

I&#39;d probably choose to refactor even further, adding at least one if
not more private methods to, in Ron&#39;s words, &quot;improve expressiveness&quot;.
But limiting it to just what is here, I&#39;m curious how you&#39;d choose to
refactor this, what tests you would need to add, a comparison of the
amount of code and number of classes a developer would have to sift
through to understand the this vs. your ideal implementation.

Jim
